		<b>Comment By mbartley, 4-08-09</b>
		<p>Shoot Jenny, you've completely shattered my plan. Self-publish a first draft novel about overcoming. Send the three hundred and three page novel to Oprah to discover. Bask in the glory of modern media charmed by my backstory. Receive an exceptionally large advance on my next novel and, of course, my highly anticipated memoir filled with more overcoming. Buy some land near a little know but stunningly wild and beautiful National Forest and live the rest of my days in peace and comfort and wonderment. Oh well, I guess writing is actually work. Who would have thought. Guess, I'll try my hand at graphic novels complete with my own stick man, sorry stick person, drawings. Next stop Hollywood and glory. At the Oscar's,  I'll be sure and include you along with my agent, gopher, and other assorted members of my real west posse. Now, let's talk about slapping that first novel of yours between some leather so you too can become a personality. Whoopie tie yay.<br />
Michael</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Heather Sharfeddin, 4-08-09</b>
		<p>My basement is the scariest place in North America. It has four unpublished novels!</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Allen Jones, 4-08-09</b>
		<p>By and large, seems like most second and even third novels deserve a place in that basement as well. The only way fiction can justify itself is by being extraordinary, and the only way to succeed at that level is to fail, and fail, and fail, until finally you can hit one out of the park. Perhaps because the art and craft of fiction lies in making it look easy, in making the reading experience effortless, most writers assume, starting out, that it must actually BE easy. But good rule of thumb: If it's easy write, it's probably not worth reading.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Melanie, 4-08-09</b>
		<p>But wait. What if you don't have aspirations to be Faulkner, but instead aspire to be Nora Roberts? Or maybe not even Nora Roberts, but someone a few rungs lower on that particular totem pole? Then I would say the opposite should apply. The more nauseatingly hopeful and sweeping your work of fiction is, the better your chances for publishing, right? Right? Please say I'm right.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Michael Pokocky, 4-09-09</b>
		<p>Sorry to say but your post anchors itself in the idea to go for the prize.<br />
Not only that but you do not mention anywhere your credentials as a expert on the publishing industry and as a writer.<br />
So what am I to conclude.  I will reserve my comments on that.<br />
What is important to anyone reading this is that there will always be someone out there that is so believable  that one might just take their advice.  The newbie novelist is desperate for attention and desires to be the next Hemingway. <br />
What about writing because you like to write?  What about talking about the joys you experienced as a writer?  Why not talk about the hard work and the idea that writing if taken seriously is a profession with no guarantees of ever getting paid?  Why talk about yourself and your prize and then devaluing the very thing that motivated you to continue on in one of the most dreaded hardest professions out there?<br />
Perhaps you can write a post to answer some of my questions as an update or part II to this post where you get to tell us the life of a writer like yourself.  Aren't you happy you are a writer and does it not all boil down at the end of the day all a writer wants is to be read?<br />
Kindest,<br />
Michael</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Jenny Shank, 4-09-09</b>
		<p>Thanks for your comments, everybody.  Melanie--you're right, cynicism will not help people with aspirations to write hopeful, sweeping books.  But maybe cynicism will help you figure out what sorts of stuff fans of these kinds of books are suckers for, so you can produce that?<br />
<br />
Michael P.: as for credentials on the writing and publishing industry, I have none.  Except that I read a lot.  A couple of books a week.  But I am an "expert" in nothing.  So don't listen to me, follow your dreams, man.</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Clive Warner, 4-09-09</b>
		<p>Oh yes, I totally agree. My own first novel was dreadful. The second one not bad but not publishable. Often it is the third novel that gets published. Then your fourth one comes out and you look at the third one with the benefit of added time and think, oh hell, it should have been better ...</p>
		
		<b>Comment By Ev Bishop, 4-09-09</b>
		<p>Dear Jenny,<br />
<br />
Great post and great affirmation.   Sometimes I feel a bit of guilt about my basement novel--did I give up on it too quickly?  And then I remember all of its vehement, heartfelt messages....  ;-D  <br />
